Die snoek loop teen die Weskus en vissermanne van Lambertsbaai tot in St Helenabaai kry goeie vangste met van die skuite wat soveel as 800 snoeke aan wal bring. Die enigste probleem vir die vissermanne is dat die nasionale inperkings tot gevolg gehad het dat die aanvraag na snoek baie laer is as vorige jare. Snoek het vir tussen R130 tot R150 voor paasfees op die kaai verkoop maar die prys is nou onder R50 'n snoek in die hawe. foto: Jaco Marais If Ali Tabriziâ€™s documentary Seaspiracy, released in March, left you tutting at the fish section in the supermarket, ready to enlist in the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society or just plain paralysed with panic at the depth and vastness of the problems the worldâ€™s oceans are currently facing, you are not alone.  Comments like: â€œwatched it today and damn iâ€™m never eating seafood againâ€, â€œ@seaspiracy where do I sign up to be a sea shepherd???â€ and â€œThatâ€™s why Iâ€™m vegan. ğŸ˜®â€ have flooded Seaspiracyâ€™s Instagram page and are not uncommon sentiments in conversations with people who have come out the other side of the shocking account of the destructive environmental impacts of human activity on the oceans. Produced by the team behind the 2014 Netflix exposÃ© on environmental impacts of agriculture and the meat industry, Cowspiracy, marine biologist and WWFâ€™s environmental behaviour change practitioner and WWF-Sassi (Southern African Sustainable Seafood Institute) manager, Pavitray Pillay, who watched Seaspiracy in parts due to its intensity graphically and emotionally, commends Tabriziâ€™s exposÃ© for bringing many of the alarming ocean issues to Netflixâ€™s more than 200 million subscribers. â€œSeaspiracy highlights some real, valid issues that we have when it comes to the oceans: overfishing, illegal fishing, unregulated fishing, massive human rights infringements, issues around plastic in the oceans, issues around seafood fraud, issues around non-traceability; so from the point of bringing these problems 